# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: social-metabolism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Public access to government information, including through the open publication of information, and formal freedom of information laws, is widely considered to be an important basic component of democracy and integrity in government.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Michael Buckland defines six types of barriers that have to be overcome in order for access to information to be achieved: identification of the source, availability of the source, price of the user, cost to the provider, cognitive access, and acceptability.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] While "access to information", "right to information", "right to know" and "freedom of information" are sometimes used as synonyms, the diverse terminology does highlight particular (albeit related) dimensions of the issue.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Freedom of information is related to freedom of expression, which can apply to any medium, be it oral, writing, print, electronic, or through art forms.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This means that the protection of freedom of speech as a right includes not only the content, but also the means of expression.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Freedom of information is a separate concept which sometimes comes into conflict with the right to privacy in the context of the Internet and information technology.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] As with the right to freedom of expression, the right to privacy is a recognized human right and freedom of information acts as an extension to this right.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The government of the United Kingdom has theorised it as being an extension of freedom of speech, and a fundamental human right.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The international and United States Pirate Party have established political platforms based largely on freedom of information issues.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] There has been a significant increase in global access to the Internet, which reached just over 5.35 billion users in 2024, amounting to about 66 per cent of the world's population.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] But the digital divide continues to exclude over half of the world's population, particularly women and girls, and especially in Africa and the least developed countries as well as several Small Island Developing States.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Further, individuals with disabilities can either be advantaged or further disadvantaged by the design of technologies or through the presence or absence of training and education.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Access to information faces great difficulties because of the global digital divide.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] A digital divide is an economic and social inequality concerning access to, use of, or impact of information and communication technologies (ICT).
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The divide within countries (such as the digital divide in the United States) may refer to inequalities between individuals, households, businesses, or geographic areas, usually at different socioeconomic levels or other demographic categories.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The divide between differing countries or regions of the world is referred to as the global digital divide, examining this technological gap between developing and developed countries on an international scale.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Although many groups in society are affected by a lack of access to computers or the internet, communities of color are specifically observed to be negatively affected by the digital divide.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This is evident when it comes to observing home-internet access among different races and ethnicities.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] 81% of Whites and 83% of Asians have home internet access, compared to 70% of Hispanics, 68% of Blacks, 72% of American Indian/Alaska Natives, and 68% of Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islanders.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Although income is a factor in home-internet access disparities, there are still racial and ethnic inequalities that are present among those within lower-income groups.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] 58% of low-income Whites are reported to have home-internet access in comparison to 51% of Hispanics and 50% of Blacks.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This information is reported in a report titled "Digital Denied: The Impact of Systemic Racial Discrimination on Home-Internet Adoption" which was published by the DC-based public interest group Fress Press.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The report concludes that structural barriers and discrimination that perpetuates bias against people of different races and ethnicities contribute to having an impact on the digital divide.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The report also concludes that those who do not have internet access still have a high demand for it, and reduction in the price of home-internet access would allow for an increase in equitable participation and improve internet adoption by marginalized groups.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Digital censorship and algorithmic bias are observed to be present in the racial divide.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Hate-speech rules as well as hate-speech algorithms on online platforms such as Facebook have favored white males and those belonging to elite groups in society over marginalized groups in society, such as women and people of color.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] When the question of which subset group is protected is presented, the correct answer was white men.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Minority group language is negatively impacted by automated tools of hate detection due to human bias that ultimately decides what is considered hate speech and what is not.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Online platforms have also been observed to tolerate hateful content towards people of color but restrict content from people of color.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Aboriginal memes on a Facebook page were posted with racially abusive content and comments depicting Aboriginal people as inferior.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] While the contents on the page were removed by the originators after an investigation conducted by the Australian Communications and Media Authority, Facebook did not delete the page and has allowed it to remain under the classification of controversial humor.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] However, a post by an African American woman addressing her discomfort with being the only person of color in a small-town restaurant was met with racist and hateful messages.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] When reporting the online abuse to Facebook, her account was suspended by Facebook for three days for posting the screenshots while those responsible for the racist comments she received were not suspended.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Shared experiences between people of color can be at risk of being silenced under removal policies for online platforms.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Inequities in access to information technologies are present among individuals living with a disability in comparison to those who are not living with a disability.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to The Pew Internet 54% of households with a person who has a disability have home internet access compared to 81% of households that have home internet access and do not have a person who has a disability.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The type of disability an individual has can prevent one from interacting with computer screens and smartphone screens, such as having a quadriplegia disability or having a disability in the hands.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] However, there is still a lack of access to technology and home internet access among those who have a cognitive and auditory disability as well.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Issues such as the perception of disabilities in society, Federal and state government policy, corporate policy, mainstream computing technologies, and real-time online communication have been found to contribute to the impact of the digital divide on individuals with disabilities.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] People with disabilities are also the targets of online abuse.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Online disability hate crimes have increased by 33% within the past year across the UK according to a report published by Leonard Cheshire.org.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Accounts of online hate abuse towards people with disabilities were shared during an incident in 2019 when model Katie Price's son was the target of online abuse that was attributed to him having a disability.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In response to the abuse, a campaign was launched by Katie Price to ensure that Britain's MP's held those who are guilty of perpetuating online abuse towards those with disabilities accountable.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Online abuse towards individuals with disabilities is a factor that can discourage people from engaging online which could prevent people from learning information that could improve their lives.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Many individuals living with disabilities face online abuse in the form of accusations of benefit fraud and "faking" their disability for financial gain, which in some cases leads to unnecessary investigations.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Women's freedom of information and access to information globally is less than men's.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Social barriers such as illiteracy and lack of digital empowerment have created stark inequalities in navigating the tools used for access to information, often exacerbating lack of awareness of issues that directly relate to women and gender, such as sexual health.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] There have also been examples of more extreme measures, such as local community authorities banning or restricting mobile phone use for girls and unmarried women in their communities.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the Wharton School of Public Policy, the expansion of Information and Communication Technology (ICT) has resulted in multiple disparities that have had an impact on women's access to ICT with the gender gap being as high as 31% in some developing countries and 12% globally in 2016.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Socioeconomic barriers that result from these disparities are known as what we call the digital divide.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Among low-income countries and low-income regions alike, the high price of internet access presents a barrier to women since women are generally paid less and face an unequal burden between paid and unpaid work.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Cultural norms in certain countries may prohibit women from access to the internet and technology as well by preventing women from attaining a certain level of education or from being the breadwinners in their households, thus resulting in a lack of control in the household finances.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] However, even when women have access to ICT, the digital divide is still prevalent.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] A number of states, including some that have introduced new laws since 2010, notably censor voices from and content related to the LGBTQI community, posing serious consequences to access to information about sexual orientation and gender identity.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Digital platforms play a powerful role in limiting access to certain content, such as YouTube's 2017 decision to classify non-explicit videos with LGBTQIA themes as 'restricted', a classification designed to filter out "potentially inappropriate content".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The internet provides information that can create a safe space for marginalized groups such as the LGBTQIA community to connect with others and engage in honest dialogues and conversations that are affecting their communities.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] It can also be viewed as an agent of change for the LGBTQIA community and provide a means of engaging in social justice.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] It can allow for LGBTQIA individuals who may be living in rural areas or in areas where they are isolated to gain access to information that are not within their rural system as well as gain information from other LGBT individuals.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This includes information such as healthcare, partners, and news.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Gay Health provides online medical and health information and Gay and Lesbians Alliance Against Defamation contains online publications and news that focus on human rights campaigns and issues focused on LGBTQIA issues.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The Internet also allows LGBTQIA individuals to maintain anonymity.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Lack of access to the internet can hinder these things due to a lack of broadband access in remote rural areas.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] LGBT Tech has emphasized launching newer technologies with 5G technology to help close the digital divide that can cause members of the LGBTQIA community to lose access to reliable and fast technology that can provide information on healthcare, economic opportunities, and safe communities.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Other factors can prevent LGBTQIA members from accessing information online or subject them to having their information abused.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Internet filters are also used to censor and restrict LGBTQIA content that is in relation to the LGBTQIA community in public schools and libraries.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] There is also the presence of online abuse by online predators that target LGBTQIA members by seeking out their personal information and providing them with inaccurate information.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The use of the internet can provide a way for LGBTQIA individuals to gain access to information to deal with societal setbacks through therapeutic advice, social support systems, and an online environment that fosters a collaboration of ideas, concerns, and helps LGBTQIA individuals move forward.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This can be fostered through human service professionals who can utilize the internet with evidence and evaluation to provide information to LGBTQIA individuals who are dealing with the circumstances of coming out and the possible repercussions that could follow as a result.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Freedom of information (or information freedom) also refers to the protection of the right to freedom of expression with regard to the Internet and information technology.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Freedom of information may also concern censorship in an information technology context, i.e. the ability to access Web content, without censorship or restrictions.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to Kuzmin and Parshakova, access to information entails learning in formal and informal education settings.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] It also entails fostering the competencies of information and media literacy that enable users to be empowered and make full use of access to the Internet.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] UNESCO's support for journalism education is an example of how UNESCO seeks to contribute to the provision of independent and verifiable information accessible in cyberspace.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Promoting access for disabled persons has been strengthened by the UNESCO-convened conference in 2014, which adopted the "New Delhi Declaration on Inclusive ICTs for Persons with Disabilities: Making Empowerment a Reality".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the International Telecommunication Union (ITU), "Open Standards" are standards made available to the general public and developed (or approved) and maintained via a collaborative and consensus-driven process.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS) Declaration of Principles adopted in 2003 reaffirms democracy and the universality, indivisibility and interdependence of all human rights and fundamental freedoms.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The 2004 WSIS Declaration of Principles also acknowledged that "it is necessary to prevent the use of information resources and technologies for criminal and terrorist purposes, while respecting human rights".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Wolfgang Benedek comments that the WSIS Declaration only contains a number of references to human rights and does not spell out any procedures or mechanism to assure that human rights are considered in practice.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The digital rights group Hacktivismo, founded in 1999, argues that access to information is a basic human right.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The group's beliefs are described fully in the "Hacktivismo Declaration" which calls for the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR) to be applied to the Internet.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The Declaration recalls the duty of member states to the ICCPR to protect the right to freedom of expression with regard to the internet and in this context freedom of information.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] On October 29, 2008, the Global Network Initiative (GNI) was founded upon its "Principles on Freedom of Expression and Privacy".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Participants in the Initiative include the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Human Rights Watch, Google, Microsoft, Yahoo, other major companies, human rights NGOs, investors, and academics.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to reports, Cisco Systems was invited to the initial discussions but did not take part in the initiative.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Harrington Investments, which proposed that Cisco establish a human rights board, has dismissed the GNI as a voluntary code of conduct not having any impact.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Chief executive John Harrington called the GNI "meaningless noise" and instead calls for bylaws to be introduced that force boards of directors to accept human rights responsibilities.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Jo Glanville, editor of the Index on Censorship, states that "the internet has been a revolution for censorship as much as for free speech".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The concept of freedom of information has emerged in response to state-sponsored censorship, monitoring and surveillance of the internet.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Internet censorship includes the control or suppression of the publishing or accessing of information on the Internet.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the Reporters without Borders (RSF) "internet enemy list" the following states engage in pervasive internet censorship: Cuba, Iran, Maldives, Myanmar/Burma, North Korea, Syria, Tunisia, Uzbekistan and Vietnam.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] A widely publicised example is the so-called "Great Firewall of China" (in reference both to its role as a network firewall and to the ancient Great Wall of China).
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The system blocks content by preventing IP addresses from being routed through and consists of standard firewalls and proxy servers at the Internet gateways.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The system also selectively engages in DNS poisoning when particular sites are requested.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The government does not appear to be systematically examining Internet content, as this appears to be technically impractical.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China is conducted under a wide variety of laws and administrative regulations.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In accordance with these laws, more than sixty Internet regulations have been made by the People's Republic of China (PRC) government, and censorship systems are vigorously implemented by provincial branches of state-owned ISPs, business companies, and organizations.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton, speaking on behalf of the United States, declared 'we stand for a single internet where all of humanity has equal access to knowledge and ideas'.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The increasing access to and reliance on digital media to receive and produce information have increased the possibilities for States and private sector companies to track individuals’ behaviors, opinions and networks.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] States have increasingly adopted laws and policies to legalize monitoring of communication, justifying these practices with the need to defend their own citizens and national interests.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In parts of Europe, new anti-terrorism laws have enabled a greater degree of government surveillance and an increase in the ability of intelligence authorities to access citizens’ data.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] While legality is a precondition for legitimate limitations of human rights, the issue is also whether a given law is aligned to other criteria for justification such as necessity, proportionality and legitimate purpose.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The United Nations Human Rights Council has taken a number of steps to highlight the importance of the universal right to privacy online.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In 2015, in a resolution on the right to privacy in the digital age, it established a United Nations Special Rapporteur on the Right to Privacy.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Number of regional efforts, particularly through the courts, to establish regulations that deal with data protection, privacy and surveillance, and which affect their relationship to journalistic uses.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The Council of Europe’s Convention 108, the Convention for the protection of individuals with regard to automatic processing of personal data, has undergone a modernization process to address new challenges to privacy.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Since 2012, four new countries belonging to the Council of Europe have signed or ratified the Convention, as well as three countries that do not belong to the Council, from Africa and Latin America.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Regional courts are also playing a noteworthy role in the development of online privacy regulations.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In 2016, the European Commission and United States Government reached an agreement to replace Safe Harbour, the EU-U.S.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Privacy Shield, which includes data protection obligations on companies receiving personal data from the European Union, safeguards on United States government access to data, protection and redress for individuals, and an annual joint review to monitor implementation.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The European Court of Justice's 2014 decision in the Google Spain case allowed people to claim a "right to be forgotten" or "right to be de-listed" in a much-debated approach to the balance between privacy, free expression and transparency.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Following the Google Spain decision the "right to be forgotten" or "right to be de-listed" has been recognized in a number of countries across the world, particularly in Latin America and the Caribbean.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Recital 153 of the European Union General Data Protection Regulation states "Member States law should reconcile the rules governing freedom of expression and information, including journalistic...with the right to the protection of personal data pursuant to this Regulation.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The number of countries around the world with data protection laws has also continued to grow.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the World Trends Report 2017/2018, between 2012 and 2016, 20 UNESCO Member States adopted data protection laws for the first time, bringing the global total to 101.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Of these new adoptions, nine were in Africa, four in Asia and the Pacific, three in Latin America and the Caribbean, two in the Arab region and one in Western Europe and North America.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] During the same period, 23 countries revised their data protection laws, reflecting the new challenges to data protection in the digital era.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to Global Partners Digital, only four States have secured in national legislation a general right to encryption, and 31 have enacted national legislation that grants law enforcement agencies the power to intercept or decrypt encrypted communications.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Since 2010, to increase the protection of the information and communications of their users and promoted trust in their services.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] High-profile examples of this have been WhatsApp's implementation of full end-to-end encryption in its messenger service, and Apple's contestation of a law enforcement warrant to unlock an iPhone used by the perpetrators of a terror attack.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Rapid changes in the digital environment, coupled with contemporary journalist practice that increasingly relies on digital communication technologies, pose new risks for the protection of journalism sources.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Leading contemporary threats include mass surveillance technologies, mandatory data retention policies, and disclosure of personal digital activities by third-party intermediaries.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Without a thorough understanding of how to shield their digital communications and traces, journalists and sources can unwittingly reveal identifying information.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Employment of national security legislation, such as counter-terrorism laws, to override existing legal protections for source protection is also becoming a common practice.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In many regions, persistent secrecy laws or new cybersecurity laws threaten the protection of sources, such as when they give governments the right to intercept online communications in the interest of overly broad definitions of national security.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Developments regarding source protection laws have occurred between 2007 and mid-2015 in 84 (69 per cent) of the 121 countries surveyed.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] As of 2015, at least 60 nations had adopted some form of whistle-blower protection.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] At the international level, the United Nations Convention against Corruption entered into force in 2005.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] By July 2017, the majority of countries around the globe, 179 in total, had ratified the convention, which includes provisions for the protection of whistleblowers.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Regional conventions against corruption that contain protection for whistle-blowers have also been widely ratified.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] These include the Inter-American Convention Against Corruption, which has been ratified by 33 Member States, and the African Union Convention on Preventing and Combating Corruption, which was ratified by 36 UNESCO Member States.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In 2009, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) Council adopted the Recommendation for Further Combating Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the World Trends Report, access to a variety of media increased between 2012 and 2016.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The internet has registered the highest growth in users supported by massive investments in infrastructure and significant uptake in mobile usage.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the International Telecommunication Union (ITU), by the end of 2017, an estimated 48 per cent of individuals regularly connect to the internet, up from 34 per cent in 2012.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Despite the significant increase in absolute numbers, however, in the same period the annual growth rate of internet users has slowed down, with five per cent annual growth in 2017, dropping from a 10 per cent growth rate in 2012.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The number of unique mobile cellular subscriptions increased from 3.89 billion in 2012 to 4.83 billion in 2016, two-thirds of the world’s population, with more than half of subscriptions located in Asia and the Pacific.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The number of subscriptions is predicted to rise to 5.69 billion users in 2020.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] As of 2016, almost 60 per cent of the world’s population had access to a 4G broadband cellular network, up from almost 50 per cent in 2015 and 11 per cent in 2012.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The limits that users face on accessing information via mobile applications coincide with a broader process of fragmentation of the internet.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Zero-rating, the practice of internet providers allowing users free connectivity to access specific content or applications for free, has offered some opportunities for individuals to surmount economic hurdles, but has also been accused by its critics of creating a 'two-tiered' internet.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] To address the issues with zero-rating, an alternative model has emerged in the concept of ‘equal rating’ and is being tested in experiments by Mozilla and Orange in Africa.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Equal rating prevents prioritization of one type of content and zero-rates all content up to a specified data cap.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Some countries in the region had a handful of plans to choose from (across all mobile network operators) while others, such as Colombia, offered as many as 30 pre-paid and 34 post-paid plans.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In Western Europe and North America, the primacy of television as a main source of information is being challenged by the internet, while in other regions, such as Africa, television is gaining greater audience share than radio, which has historically been the most widely accessed media platform.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Age plays a profound role in determining the balance between radio, television and the internet as the leading source of news.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the 2017 Reuters Institute Digital News Report, in 36 countries and territories surveyed, 51 per cent of adults 55 years and older consider television as their main news source, compared to only 24 per cent of respondents between 18 and 24.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The pattern is reversed when it comes to online media, chosen by 64 per cent of users between 18 and 24 as their primary source, but only by 28 per cent of users 55 and older.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] According to the Arab Youth Survey, in 2016, 45 percent of the young people interviewed considered social media as a major source of news.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Satellite television has continued to add global or transnational alternatives to national viewing options for many audiences.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Reflecting a more outward-looking orientation, China Global Television Network (CGTN), the multi-language and multi-channel grouping owned and operated by China Central Television, changed its name from CCTV-NEWS in January 2017.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] After years of budget cuts and shrinking global operations, in 2016 BBC announced the launch of 12 new language services (in Afaan Oromo, Amharic, Gujarati, Igbo, Korean, Marathi, Pidgin, Punjabi, Telugu, Tigrinya, and Yoruba), branded as a component of its biggest expansion ‘since the 1940s’.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Also expanding access to content are changes in usage patterns with non-linear viewing, as online streaming is becoming an important component of users’ experience.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Since expanding its global service to 130 new countries in January 2016, Netflix experienced a surge in subscribers, surpassing 100 million subscribers in the second quarter of 2017, up from 40 million in 2012.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The audience has also become more diverse with 47 per cent of users based outside of the United States, where the company began in 1997.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The Internet has challenged the press as an alternative source of information and opinion but has also provided a new platform for newspaper organizations to reach new audiences.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Between 2012 and 2016, print newspaper circulation continued to fall in almost all regions, except Asia and the Pacific, where the dramatic increase in sales in a few select countries has offset falls in historically strong Asian markets such as Japan and the Republic of Korea.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Between 2012 and 2016, India’s print circulation grew by 89 per cent.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] As many newspapers make the transition to online platforms, revenues from digital subscriptions and digital advertising have been growing significantly.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] How to capture more of this growth remains a pressing challenge for newspapers.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development, adopted by the United Nations General Assembly in September 2015, includes Goal 16.10 to ‘ensure public access to information and protect fundamental freedoms, in accordance with national legislation and international agreements’.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] UNESCO has been assigned as the custodian agency responsible for global reporting on indicator 16.10.2 regarding the ‘number of countries that adopt and implement constitutional, statutory and/or policy guarantees for public access to information’.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This responsibility aligns with UNESCO's commitment to promote universal access to information, grounded in its constitutional mandate to ‘promote the free flow of ideas by word and image’.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In 2015, UNESCO's General Conference proclaimed 28 September as the International Day for Universal Access to Information.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The following year, participants of UNESCO's annual celebration of World Press Freedom Day adopted the Finlandia Declaration on access to information and fundamental freedoms, 250 years after the first freedom of information law was adopted in what is modern day Finland and Sweden.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The International Programme for the Development of Communication (IPDC) is a United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) programme aimed at strengthening the development of mass media in developing countries.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The International Programme for the Development of Communication is responsible for the follow-up of the Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) 16 through indicators 16.10.1 and 16.10.2.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Every two years, a report containing information from the Member States on the status of judicial inquiries on each of the killings condemned by UNESCO is submitted to the IPDC Council by UNESCO's Director-General.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The journalists safety indicators are a tool developed by UNESCO which, according to UNESCO's website, aims on mapping the key features that can help assess safety of journalists, and help determine whether adequate follow-up is given to crimes committed against them.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The IPDC Talks also allow the Programme to raise awareness of the importance of access to information.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The IPDC is also the programme that monitors and reports on access to information laws around the world through the United Nations Secretary-General global report on follow-up to SDGs.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] On 28 September 2015, UNESCO adopted the International Day for the Universal Access to Information during its 38th session.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] During the International Day, the IPDC organized the "IPDC Talks: Powering Sustainable Development with Access to Information" event, which gathered high-level participants.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The annual event aims on highlighting the "importance of access to information" for sustainable development.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The concept is based on four principles stressing that the Internet should be Human rights-based, Open, Accessible, and based on Multistakeholder participation.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] These have been abbreviated as the R-O-A-M principles.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Through the concept of internet universality UNESCO highlights access to information as a key to assess a better Internet environment.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] There is special relevance to the Internet of the broader principle of social inclusion.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] This puts forward the role of accessibility in overcoming digital divides, digital inequalities, and exclusions based on skills, literacy, language, gender or disability.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] It also points to the need for sustainable business models for Internet activity, and to trust in the preservation, quality, integrity, security, and authenticity of information and knowledge.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Accessibility is interlinked to rights and openness.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Based on the ROAM principles, UNESCO is now developing Internet Universality indicators to help governments and other stakeholders assess their own national Internet environments and to promote the values associated with Internet Universality, such as access to information.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In 2010, the World Bank launched the World Bank policy on access to information, which constitutes a major shift in the World Bank's strategy.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The World Bank is prone to Open Developments with its Open data, Open Finance and Open knowledge repository.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The World Summit on the Information Society (WSIS) was a two-phase United Nations-sponsored summit on information, communication and, in broad terms, the information society that took place in 2003 in Geneva and in 2005 in Tunis.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] One of its chief aims was to bridge the global digital divide separating rich countries from poor countries by spreading access to the Internet in the developing world.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The conferences established 17 May as World Information Society Day.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The results from UNESCO monitoring of SDG 16.10.2 show that 112 countries have now adopted freedom of information legislation or similar administrative regulations.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] Of these, 22 adopted new legislation since 2012.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] At the regional level, Africa has seen the highest growth, with 10 countries adopting freedom of information legislation in the last five years, more than doubling the number of countries in the region to have such legislation from nine to 19.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] A similarly high growth rate has occurred in the Asia-Pacific region, where seven countries adopted freedom of information laws in the last five years, bringing the total to 22.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] In addition, during the reporting period, two countries in the Arab region, two countries in Latin America and the Caribbean, and one country in Western Europe and North America adopted freedom of information legislation.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p01] The vast majority of the world's population now lives in a country with a freedom of information law, and several countries currently have freedom of information bills under consideration.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In June 2006, nearly 70 countries had freedom of information legislation applying to information held by government bodies and in certain circumstances to private bodies.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In 19 of these countries, the freedom of information legislation also applied to private bodies.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Access to information was increasingly recognised as a prerequisite for transparency and accountability of governments, as facilitating consumers' ability to make informed choices, and as safeguarding citizens against mismanagement and corruption.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] This has led an increasing number of countries to enact freedom of information legislation in the past 10 years.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In recent years, private bodies have started to perform functions which were previously carried out by public bodies.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Privatisation and deregulation saw banks, telecommunications companies, hospitals and universities being run by private entities, leading to demands for the extension of freedom of information legislation to cover private bodies.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] While there has been an increase in countries with freedom of information laws, their implementation and effectiveness vary considerably across the world.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] The Global Right to Information Rating is a programme providing advocates, legislators, and reformers with tools to assess the strength of a legal framework.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In measuring the strength and legal framework of each country's freedom of information law using the Right to Information Rating, one notable trend appears.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Largely regardless of geographic location, top-scoring countries tend to have younger laws.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Despite the adoption of freedom of information laws, officials are often unfamiliar with the norms of transparency at the core of freedom of information or are unwilling to recognize them in practice.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Debates around public access to information have also focused on further developments in encouraging open data approaches to government transparency.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In 2009, the data.gov portal was launched in the United States, collecting in one place most of the government open data; in the years following, there was a wave of government data opening around the world.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In 2015 the Open Data Charter was founded in a multistakeholder process in order to establish principles for ‘how governments should be publishing information’.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] The Charter has been adopted by 17 national governments half of which were from Latin America and the Caribbean.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] The 2017 Open Data Barometer, conducted by the World Wide Web Foundation, shows that while 79 out of the 115 countries surveyed have open government data portals, in most cases "the right policies are not in place, nor is the breadth and quality of the data-sets released sufficient".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In general, the Open Data Barometer found that government data is usually "incomplete, out of date, of low quality, and fragmented".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] The degree to which private bodies are covered under freedom of information legislation varies; in Angola, Armenia and Peru the legislation only applies to private companies that perform what are considered to be public functions.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In the Czech Republic, the Dominican Republic, Finland, Trinidad and Tobago, Slovakia, Poland and Iceland private bodies that receive public funding are subject to freedom of information legislation.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Freedom of information legislation in Estonia, France and UK covers private bodies in certain sectors.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In South Africa the access provisions of the Promotion of Access to Information Act have been used by individuals to establish why their loan application has been denied.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] The access provisions have also been used by minority shareholders in private companies and environmental groups, who were seeking information on the potential environmental damage caused by company projects.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] In 1983, the United Nations Commission on Transnational Corporations adopted the United Nations Guidelines for Consumer Protection stipulating eight consumer rights, including "consumer access to adequate information to enable making informed choices according to individual wishes and needs".
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Access to information became regarded as a basic consumer right, and preventive disclosure, i.e. the disclosure of information on threats to human lives, health and safety, began to be emphasized.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Secretive decision-making by company directors and corporate scandals led to freedom of information legislation being published for the benefit of investors.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Such legislation was first adopted in Britain in the early 20th century, and later in North America and other countries.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Disclosure regimes for the benefit of investors regained attention at the beginning of the 21st century as a number of corporate scandals were linked to accounting fraud and company director secrecy.
[src:social-metabolism/access-to-information-p02] Starting with Enron, the subsequent scandals involving Worldcom, Tyco, Adelphia and Global Crossing prompted the US Congress to impose new information disclosure obligations on companies with the Sarbanes-Oxley Act 2002.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] An **agrarian society**, or **agricultural society**, is any community whose economy is based on producing and maintaining crops and farmland.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Another way to define an agrarian society is by seeing how much of a nation's total production is in agriculture.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] In agrarian society, cultivating the land is the primary source of wealth.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Such a society may acknowledge other means of livelihood and work habits but stresses the importance of agriculture and farming.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarian societies have existed in various parts of the world as far back as 10,000 years ago and continue to exist today.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] They have been the most common form of socio-economic organization for most of recorded human history.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarian society was preceded by hunters and gatherers and horticultural societies and transitioned into industrial society.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The transition to agriculture, called the Neolithic Revolution, has taken place independently multiple times.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Horticulture and agriculture as types of subsistence developed among humans somewhere between 10,000 and 8,000 years ago in the Fertile Crescent region of the Middle East.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The reasons for the development of agriculture are debated but may have included climate change, and the accumulation of food surplus for competitive gift-giving.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Most certainly there was a gradual transition from hunter-gatherer to agricultural economies after a lengthy period when some crops were deliberately planted and other foods were gathered from the wild.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] An example of this transition can be found in the cultivation of wild cereals by hunter-gatherers in the Central Sahara.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] In addition to the emergence of farming in the Fertile Crescent, agriculture appeared: by at least 6,800 BCE in East Asia (rice) and, later, in Central and South America (maize and squash).
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Small-scale agriculture also likely arose independently in early Neolithic contexts in India (rice) and Southeast Asia (taro).
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] However, full dependency on domestic crops and animals, when wild resources contributed a nutritionally insignificant component to the diet, did not occur until the Bronze Age.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agriculture allows a much greater density of population than can be supported by hunting and gathering and allows for the accumulation of excess product to keep for winter use or to sell for profit.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The ability of farmers to feed large numbers of people whose activities have nothing to do with material production was the crucial factor in the rise of surplus, specialization, advanced technology, hierarchical social structures, inequality, and standing armies.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarian societies thus support the emergence of a more complex social structure.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] In agrarian societies, some of the simple correlations between social complexity and environment begin to disappear.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] One view is that humans with this technology have moved a large step toward controlling their environments, are less dependent on them, and hence show fewer correlations between environment and technology-related traits.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] A rather different view is that as societies become larger and the movement of goods and people cheaper, they incorporate an increasing range of environmental variation within their borders and trade system.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] But environmental factors may still play a strong role as variables that affect the internal structure and history of a society in complex ways.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] For example, the average size of agrarian states will depend on the ease of transportation, major cities will tend to be located at trade nodes, and the demographic history of a society may depend on disease episodes.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] It is now clear that agriculture was adopted despite certain disadvantages of that lifestyle.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Archeological studies show that health deteriorated in populations that adopted cereal agriculture, returning to pre-agricultural levels only in modern times.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] This is in part attributable to the spread of infection in crowded cities, but is largely due to a decline in dietary quality that accompanied intensive cereal farming.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] People in many parts of the world remained hunter-gatherers until quite recently; though they were quite aware of the existence and methods of agriculture, they declined to undertake it.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Many explanations have been offered, usually centered around a particular factor that forced the adoption of agriculture, such as environmental or population pressure.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Main source of income was cultivation and farming.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarian societies transition into industrial societies when less than half of their population is directly engaged in agricultural production.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Such societies started appearing because of the Commercial and Industrial Revolution which can be seen beginning in the Mediterranean city-states from 1000 to 1500 CE.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] As European societies developed during the Middle Ages, classical knowledge was reacquired from scattered sources, and a new series of maritime commercial societies developed again in Europe.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The initial developments were centered in Northern Italy, in the city-states of Venice, Florence, Milan, and Genoa.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] By about 1500 a few of these city-states probably met the requirements of having half of their populations engaged in non-agricultural pursuits and became commercial societies.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] These small states were highly urbanized, imported much food, and were centers of trade and manufacture to a degree quite unlike typical agrarian societies.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The culminating development, still in progress, was the development of industrial technology, the application of mechanical sources of energy to an ever-increasing number of production problems.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] By about 1800, the agricultural population of Britain had sunk to about one third of the total.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] By mid-19th century, all the countries of Western Europe, plus the United States of America had more than half their populations in non-farm occupations.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Even today, the Industrial Revolution is far from completely replacing agrarianism with industrialism.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Only a minority of the world's population today live in industrialized societies although most predominantly agrarian societies have a significant industrial sector.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The use of crop breeding, better management of soil nutrients, and improved weed control have greatly increased yields per unit area.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] At the same time, the use of mechanization has decreased labor input.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The developing world generally produces lower yields, having less of the latest science, capital, and technology base.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] More people in the world are involved in agriculture as their primary economic activity than in any other activity, yet it only accounts for four percent of the world's GDP.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The rapid rise of mechanization in the 20th century, especially in the form of the tractor, reduced the necessity of humans performing the demanding tasks of sowing, harvesting, and threshing.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] With mechanization, these tasks could be performed with a speed and on a scale barely imaginable before.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] These advances have resulted in a substantial increase in the yield of agricultural techniques that have also translated into a decline in the percentage of populations in developed countries that are required to work in agriculture to feed the rest of the population.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The main demographic consequences of agrarian technology were simply a continuation of the trend toward higher population densities and larger settlements.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The latter is probably a more secure consequence of agrarian technology than the former.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] In principle livestock compete with humans for food and in some environments, advanced horticultural techniques can probably support more people per square kilometer than agrarian techniques.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Aside from average density, agrarian technology permitted urbanization of population to a greater extent than was possible under horticulture for two reasons.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] First, settlement sizes grew with agrarian technology because more productive farmers freed more people for urban specialty occupations.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Second, land and maritime transportation improvements made it possible to supply great cities of 1,000,000, plus inhabitants such as Rome, Baghdad, and the Chinese capital cities.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Rome, for example, could obtain grain and other bulk raw materials from Sicily, North Africa, Egypt, and Southern France to sustain large populations, even by modern standards.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] This required maritime transport on the Mediterranean.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] It is productivity per unit of labor and transport efficiency improvements of agrarian technology that had the widest impact on the more peripheral culture core features of agrarian societies.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The populations of agrarian societies have historically fluctuated substantially around the slowly rising trend line, due to famines, disease epidemics and political disruption.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] At least at the high points, population densities often seem to have exceeded the level at which everyone could be productively employed at current levels of technology.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Malthusian deterioration, under-employment and a decline in rural and lower-class urban standards of living, ensued.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarian societies are especially noted for their extremes of social classes and rigid social mobility.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] As land is the major source of wealth, social hierarchy develops based on landownership and not labor in what is often characterized as feudalism.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The system of stratification is characterized by three coinciding contrasts: governing class versus the masses, urban minority versus peasant majority, and literate minority versus illiterate majority.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] This results in two distinct subcultures; the urban elite versus the peasant masses.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Moreover, this means that cultural differences within agrarian societies are greater than the differences between them.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The landowning strata typically combine government, religious, and military institutions to justify and enforce their ownership, and support elaborate patterns of consumption, slavery, serfdom, or peonage is commonly the lot of the primary producer.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Rulers of agrarian societies do not manage their empire for the common good or in the name of the public interest, but as a piece of property they own and can do with as they please.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Caste systems, as found in India, are much more typical of agrarian societies where lifelong agricultural routines depend upon a rigid sense of duty and discipline.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The emphasis in the modern West on personal liberties and freedoms was in large part a reaction to the steep and rigid stratification of agrarian societies.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Within agrarian societies, the primary source of energy is plant biomass.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] This means that like hunter-gatherer societies, agrarian societies are dependent on natural solar energy flows.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Thus agrarian societies are characterized by their dependence on outside energy flows, low energy density, and the limited possibilities of converting one energy form into another.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Energy radiating from the sun is primarily caught and chemically fixed by plant photosynthesis.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Then it is secondarily converted by animals and, finally, processed for human use.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Unlike hunter-gatherers, agrarianism's basic strategy is to control these flows.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] For this purpose, agrarian systems mainly use living organisms which serve as food, tools, building material.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Mechanical devices making use of wind or running water also can be used to convert natural energy flows.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The amount of energy an agrarian society can use is restricted due to the low energy density of solar radiation and the low efficiency of technology.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] To increase production, an agrarian society must either increase the intensity of production or obtain more land for expansion.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Expansion may take place either by claiming territories occupied by other communities, but expansion also may take place by claiming new ecological niches from other living species.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Societies are limited by a diminishing margin of utility in that the best lands for farming are usually already under cultivation, forcing people to move into less and less arable lands.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarianism most often refers to a social philosophy which values agrarian society as superior to industrial society and stresses the superiority of a simpler rural life as opposed to the complexity and chaos of urbanized, industrialized life.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] In this view the farmer is idealized as self-sufficient and thus independent as opposed to the paid laborer who is vulnerable and alienated in modern society.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Moreover, Agrarianism usually links working the land with morality and spiritualty and links urban life, capitalism, and technology with a loss of independence and dignity while fostering vice and weakness.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] The agricultural community, with its fellowship of labor and cooperation, is thus the model society.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarianism is similar but not identical with back-to-the-land movements.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Agrarianism concentrates on the fundamental goods of the earth, communities of more limited economic and political scale than in modern society, and on simple living—even when this shift involves questioning the "progressive" character of some recent social and economic developments.
[src:social-metabolism/agrarian-society] Thus agrarianism is not industrial farming, with its specialization on products and industrial scale.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is broadly defined as an integrative approach that examines the ecological, social and economic relationship within agricultural systems.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Dalgaard *et al*. refer to agroecology as the study of the interactions between plants, animals, humans and the environment within agricultural systems.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Francis *et al*. also use the definition in the same way, but thought it should be restricted to growing food.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is a holistic approach that seeks to reconcile agriculture and local communities with natural processes for the common benefit of nature and livelihoods.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is inherently multidisciplinary, including sciences such as agronomy, ecology, environmental science, sociology, economics, history and others.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The system properties of agroecosystems studied may include: productivity, stability, sustainability and equitability.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is not limited to any one scale; it can range from an individual gene to an entire population, or from a single field in a given farm to global systems.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Wojtkowski discusses the application of agroecology in agriculture, forestry and agroforestry in his 2002 book.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology can be described in many different approaches.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] One perspective emphasizes ecosystem agroecology, which draws from system ecology and focuses on understanding farms as integrated ecological systems.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] This approach analyzes energy flows, nutrient cycles, and the ecological interactions among biotic and abiotic components of an agroecosystem.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Other scholars identify distinct historical traditions within agroecology.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] (2003) characterize agroecology as an integrative discipline combining agronomy, ecology, sociology, and economics.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Within this view, what is often termed early integrative agroecology focuses on understanding interactions among plants, animals, humans, and their environment within agricultural landscapes.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Over time, diverse methodological approaches have emerged depending on the values and goals prioritized.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Some perspectives emphasize more quantitative, technology-driven, and ecological-analytical methods often described as “hard agroecology”.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] This multi-layered use of the term encompassing science, practice, and movement has enabled agroecology to expand from the field or farm scale to the broader food-system scale, integrating ecological, social, economic, and cultural dimensions.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] There are three varieties of agroecology that are both well defined and have a certification regime.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] These are firstly biodynamic farming, secondly organic agriculture, and thirdly Green Food (managed by China Green Food).
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] For producers, certification enables certainty and oversight and the opportunity for achieving a premium price.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] For consumers, certification provides confidence that the stated good intentions have translated into actual production practices.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Biodynamics is the oldest of the certified agroecologies, Organics is the most widely practised certified agroecology (in 188 countries), and Green Food is the newest certified agroecology and was developed in China.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The history of agroecology depends on whether it is considered a body of thought or a method of practice.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Many indigenous cultures around the world have historically applied, and still apply, practices that today would be recognized as agroecological knowledge.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Examples include Maori, Nahuatl, and many other indigenous peoples.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The Mexica people that inhabited Tenochtitlan pre-colonization of the Americas used a process called chinampas that in many ways mirrors the use of composting in sustainable agriculture today.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The use of agroecological practices such as nutrient cycling and intercropping occurs across hundreds of years and many different cultures.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Indigenous peoples also currently make up a large proportion of people using agroecological practices, and those involved in the movement to move more farming into an agroecological paradigm.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] According to Gliessman and Francis *et al*., agronomy and ecology were first linked with the study of crop ecology by Klages in 1928.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] This work is a study of where crops can best be grown.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Wezel *et al*. say the first mention of the term agroecology was in 1928, with the publication of the term by Basil Bensin.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Dalgaard *et al*. claim the German zoologist Friederichs was the first to use the name in 1930 in his book on the zoology of agriculture and forestry, followed by American crop physiologist Hansen in 1939, both using the word for the application of ecology within agriculture.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Tischler's 1965 book *Agrarökologie* may be the first to be titled 'agroecology'.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] He analyzed the different components (plants, animals, soils and climate) and their interactions within an agroecosystem as well as the impact of human agricultural management on these components.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] More books and articles using the concept of agroecosystems and the word agroecology started to appear in 1970s.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] According to Dalgaard *et al*., it probably was the concept of "process ecology" such as studied by Arthur Tansley in the 1930s which inspired Harper's 1974 concept of agroecosystems, which they consider the foundation of modern agroecology.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Dalgaard *et al*. claim Frederic Clements's investigations on ecology using social sciences, community ecology and a "landscape perspective" is agroecology, as well as Henry Gleason's investigations of the population ecology of plants using different scientific disciplines.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Ethnobotanist Efraim Hernandez X.'s work on traditional knowledge in Mexico in the 1970s led to new education programs in agroecology.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Works such as *Silent Spring* and *The Limits to Growth* caused the public to be aware of the environmental costs of agricultural production, which caused more research in sustainability starting in the 1980s.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The view that the socio-economic context are fundamental was used in the 1982 article *Agroecologia del Tropico Americano* by Montaldo, who argues that this context cannot be separated from agriculture when designing agricultural practices.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In 1985 Miguel Altieri studied how the consolidation of the farms and cropping systems impact pest populations, and Gliessman how socio-economic, technological, and ecological components gave rise to producer choices of food production systems.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In 1995, Edens *et al*. in *Sustainable Agriculture and Integrated Farming Systems* considered the economics of systems, ecological impacts, and ethics and values in agriculture.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Several social movements have adopted agroecology as part of their larger organizing strategy.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Groups like La Via Campesina have used agroecology as a method for achieving food sovereignty.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology has also been utilized by farmers to resist global agricultural development patterns associated with the green revolution.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology is an applied science that involves the adaptation of ecological concepts to the structure, performance, and management of sustainable agroecosystems.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In Latin America, agroecological practices have a long history and vary between regions but share three main approaches or levels: plot scale, farm scale, and food system scale.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agroecology in Latin American countries can be used as a tool for providing both ecological, economic, and social benefits to the communities that practice it, as well as maintaining high biodiversity and providing refuges for flora and fauna in these countries.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Garí wrote two papers for the FAO in the early 2000s about using an agroecological approach which he called "agrobiodiversity" to empower farmers to cope with the impacts of the AIDS on rural areas in Africa.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In 2011, the first encounter of agroecology trainers took place in Zimbabwe and issued the Shashe Declaration.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In Ethiopia, the Private Sector Incentives and Investments (PSii) project, following in the footprints of the Alliance of Bioversity International and CIAT (International Center for Tropical Agriculture), exemplifies the practical application of agroecology in developing nations.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In October 2024, a PSii project in the Doyogena region of Ethiopia was awarded praise from local and agricultural officials.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The project stressed the importance of practices such as rotation of faba beans and wheat to help enhance soil health, reduce chemical reliance, and increase productivity.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] These initiatives were put in place to promote climate resilient methods of agriculture and to diversify the many clusters of wheat farms in the area.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The project has shown signs of immense success in both improvements in soil quality and crop yields, which has sparked conversations about possibilities of wider adoption in similar regions throughout the local area and throughout Africa.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] The European Commission supports the use of sustainable practices such as agroecology through the Green Deal and the Farm to Fork Strategy.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Academic research areas that focus on topics related to agriculture or ecology, such as agronomy, veterinary science, environmental science, and others, are heatedly debating which model of agriculture or agroecology should be supported through policy.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] Agricultural departments of different countries support agroecology to varying degrees, with the UN perhaps its most prominent proponent**.** Debates around agroecology often reflect broader tensions in land and resource management, and Puerto Rico offers several examples of these dynamics.
[src:social-metabolism/agroecology] In recent years, conflicts have emerged over the conversion of agricultural land for large-scale solar energy projects, raising concerns among local farmers and environmental groups about food security, land sovereignty, and long-term projects of fertile soil.
[src:social-metabolism/agrowth] The concept has been particularly discussed in the context of environmental policy, where it is opposed to both green growth and degrowth.
[src:social-metabolism/agrowth] Agrowth is supported by many scientists.
[src:social-metabolism/agrowth] For example environmental economist Jeroen C.
[src:social-metabolism/agrowth] M. van den Bergh argues for an agnostic attitude toward economic growth.
[src:social-metabolism/agrowth] According to him, environmental policy should not be aimed at pursuing or avoiding growth in the hope of reducing environmental damage, but at direct deployment of effective instruments such as pricing externalities (for example, via environmental taxes or emission rights).
[src:social-metabolism/agrowth] Whether the economy grows, stagnates or shrinks as a result is of secondary importance.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The theory has roots in a long intellectual tradition, particularly in the work of the German idealist philosopher Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Hegel, alienation was a necessary stage in the development of Spirit (*Geist*), in which it externalises itself in the material world to achieve self-awareness.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx adapted Hegel's dialectical framework but rejected its idealism, grounding the concept in material reality.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Influenced by Ludwig Feuerbach's critique of religious alienation, Marx argued that alienation was not an abstract philosophical condition but a concrete, historical consequence of the capitalist system that could be overcome.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In his analysis, Marx identified four key aspects of alienated labour.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] First, the worker is alienated from the product of their labour, which is appropriated by the capitalist and confronts the worker as a hostile power.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Second, they are alienated from the activity of production itself, which is experienced not as a fulfilling expression of creativity but as coerced, meaningless toil.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Third, this leads to alienation from their own human nature, or species-being (*Gattungswesen*), as free, conscious activity is reduced to a mere means of survival.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Finally, the worker is alienated from other people, as social relationships become reified and mediated by market exchange, fostering competition and indifference rather than community.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] A long-standing scholarly debate exists over the theory's place in Marx's work, with some arguing he abandoned the humanistic concept in his later, more "scientific" writings.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] However, many analysts contend that the theory remained a central, unifying concept throughout his intellectual development.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] They argue that concepts in his mature work, such as the fetishism of commodities in *Das Kapital*, represent a deeper elaboration of the alienation theme.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Marx, the overcoming of alienation could only be achieved through communism, a revolutionary transformation of society that would abolish private property and allow for the free, collective development of human potential.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The concept of alienation has a long history in Western thought, reflecting what scholar István Mészáros describes as "objective trends of European development, from slavery to the age of transition from capitalism to socialism".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] More primitive forms of alienation, according to George Novack, arose from the disparity between human needs and the lack of control over nature, a helplessness expressed through magic and religion.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In religion, the real relationship is reversed: man creates gods in his own image, but then prostrates himself before these creations as if they had created him.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In Judeo-Christian mythology, alienation is expressed as separation from God, originating with the "fall of man".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In this framework, humanity's self-alienation is a state from which it must be rescued.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Christianity proposes an imaginary solution to this alienation through universality, reconciling the contradictions that set people against one another.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx viewed this as an "abstract-theoretical" universality that contrasted with the "crude realism" of Judaism, which reflects the state of worldly affairs more directly.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] He argued that the "spirit of Judaism", with its practical, self-centred partiality, provided a vehicle for the development of capitalism, which reaches its perfection in the Christian world where civil society is completely separated from the state.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The secularization of the concept progressed with the rise of capitalism, where all things, no matter how sacred, were converted into saleable objects.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Thinkers of the Enlightenment began to frame the problem in social and historical terms.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The term was used by social contract theorists such as Hugo Grotius and John Locke to describe the act of "alienating" or surrendering personal sovereignty to the state.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Jean-Jacques Rousseau, a major influence, provided a powerful social critique of private property, inequality, and the dehumanising effects of "civilization".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Rousseau argued that the "complete alienation" of each individual's rights and liberties to the community as a whole was the necessary basis for a just society.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] However, he saw the alienation of sovereignty to an individual or small group as a degradation of one's being.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Rousseau's solutions remained in the realm of an abstract moral "ought", idealising a state of nature while accepting private property as a sacred foundation of civil society, thereby trapping his critique in an insoluble contradiction.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The German idealist philosopher Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel adapted the concept of alienation (*Entfremdung*).
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] His predecessors, such as Friedrich Schiller, discussed themes of social fragmentation and the division of humanity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Early in his career, Hegel described industrial society as "a vast system of mutual interdependence, a moving life of the dead.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Hegel, the first sense of alienation (discord) is overcome through the second (surrender), leading to a higher form of unity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Hegel, man is alienated because human labour is alienated.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Hegel, this results in an "unhappy consciousness" where man is doomed to frustration unless the severed parts of his world—subject and object, reason and reality—can be reunited.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Hegel also used the term *Entäusserung* (externalisation or objectification) to describe the process of the Spirit (*Geist*) becoming aware of itself.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Hegel, alienation was identical to objectification, a necessary stage in the development of the Absolute Idea where the Spirit externalises itself in the objective world.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] This process culminates in the Spirit's "reconciliation" with itself, overcoming the alienation by recognising the objective world as its own creation.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] However, according to Mészáros, this supersession (*Aufhebung*) is a purely conceptual one, an "imaginary transcendence" that leaves the actual material conditions of society unchanged.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Hegel's standpoint remains that of political economy, an "uncritical positivism" that accepts the foundations of capitalist society.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] While Marx rejected Hegel's idealism, he retained his relational framework, which was based on the philosophy of internal relations, but applied it to the material world of social and economic activity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx transformed Hegel's concept from an eternal, anthropological notion into a transitory, historical one, arguing that while objectification is a universal aspect of labour, alienation is a specific result of commodity production and can be overcome.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx developed his theory of alienation over several years of intellectual engagement with philosophy, law, politics, and economics.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] His fascination with the term "alienation" stemmed from its dual role in Hegelian philosophy, where it described the development of the Spirit, and in political economy, where it referred to the transfer of property.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Another significant influence was Ludwig Feuerbach, whose theory of religious alienation, presented in *The Essence of Christianity* (1841), argued that humans project their own essential qualities onto a divine being, thereby alienating themselves from their own nature.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx's project was to apply Feuerbach's "transformative method" to Hegel, reducing the abstract concept of alienation to its concrete basis in economic activity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In his 1841 doctoral thesis, Marx analysed Epicurean philosophy as an expression of a historical stage dominated by the "privatization of life" and the principle of *bellum omnium contra omnes* ("the war of all against all"), an early formulation of the atomistic nature of bourgeois society.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] According to Ernest Mandel, Marx's engagement with alienation began with the political alienation of the citizen from the state, to which he shifted his focus in his subsequent journalistic work.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Incidents such as new laws criminalising the collection of firewood by peasants in the Rhine province led Marx to conclude that the state represented the interests of private property owners, leading to a forfeiture of rights by the general populace to a hostile institution.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] A major turning point occurred in late 1843 and early 1844, when Marx moved to Paris and intensified his studies of the French Revolution and English political economy.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In his essay *On the Jewish Question*, he expanded his critique beyond the state to the entirety of bourgeois society, identifying money as a key alienating force that mediates all human relations.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] He identified a fundamental contradiction in modern society: the divorce of the individual's "objective being" from the community, reducing social ties to merely external determinations and individual existence to the ultimate end.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] It was here that he first identified the proletariat as the historical agent of universal human emancipation.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The definitive synthesis of these ideas occurred in the *Economic and Philosophic Manuscripts of 1844*.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Influenced by Friedrich Engels's *Outlines of a Critique of Political Economy*, and the writings of Moses Hess, Marx located the root of all forms of alienation in alienated labour (*entfremdete Arbeit*).
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] This concept became the "Archimedean point" of his entire system, allowing him to ground his critique of capitalism in the concrete, material process of production and to reformulate the problem of transcendence not as a philosophical "ought" but as a practical, historical necessity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The *Manuscripts* constitute what Mészáros calls Marx's "first comprehensive system" and a "synthesis in *statu nascendi*" (in a nascent state), which systematically explores the far-reaching implications of the alienation of labour in every sphere of human activity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx's theory is grounded in his conception of human nature and its distortion by capitalism.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] He views man not as an isolated individual but as a social being whose essence is realised through productive activity, or labour.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] According to scholar Bertell Ollman, to understand alienation, one must first grasp Marx's philosophy of internal relations, which posits that entities are constituted by their connections to other entities in a dynamic, organic whole.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] From this perspective, alienation is the process by which these internally related components of human nature are "splintered", "separated", and reorganised to appear as independent and even hostile to one another.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Fusing Hegel's two senses of alienation, Marx developed a single concept of "separation through surrender", where every form of alienation is rooted in the surrender of control over one's labour to another person.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In contrast to Hegel, Marx conceived of alienation not as an ontological condition of labour, but as a specific phenomenon occurring within the historical context of capitalism and wage labour, which could be overcome through "the emancipation of society from private property".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Alienation can only be comprehended as the absence of a future state of unalienation—communism—which serves as the point of reference for the critique.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Thus, alienation is not a moral judgment but a "statement of 'fact'" about the separation of humanity from its own potential.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In the *Economic and Philosophic Manuscripts of 1844*, Marx identified four principal aspects of alienated labour in capitalist society.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Alienation of the worker from the activity of production: The work that the worker performs does not belong to them but is a means to an end.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] It is "coerced labour", not a voluntary act of self-fulfilment.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] It is "not the satisfaction of a need; it is merely a means to satisfy needs external to it".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The activity itself is alien, "forced labour", and does not offer satisfaction; it "mortifies his body and ruins his mind".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Consequently, the worker "only feels himself outside his work, and in his work feels outside himself".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] This is self-estrangement (*Selbstentfremdung*).
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The labour is not spontaneous but is directed by an "alien will", that of the capitalist, making it "the loss of his own self".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] All the time sold to the employer belongs to the employer, who dictates the worker's every action, a form of control perfected in time and motion studies.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Alienation of the worker from their species-being: For Marx, humanity's "species-being" (*Gattungswesen*) is its essence as a free, conscious, and creative producer.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Humans, unlike animals, produce universally and can contemplate themselves in a world they have created.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Alienated labour reduces this free, conscious activity to a mere means for individual physical existence.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] It estranges man's "own body from him, as it does external nature and his spiritual existence, his human being".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The human "capacity to perform creative work, becomes thwarted and distorted", as the worker's special traits and abilities are not needed or developed.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The "unique configuration of relations which distinguishes the individual as a human being has been transformed into something quite different".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The worker is dehumanised, reduced to the level of an animal or a machine in their productive life, a slave in their social life, and possessing a merely brutish, uncultivated sensibility.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The critique is not that capitalism violates a pre-existing fixed nature, but that it actively produces an alienated one, as the dominant mode of production gives rise to the very construction of consciousness and personality.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Alienation of the worker from other people: Since the worker's own activity and its product are alien to them, their relationship with other people is also alienated.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] More broadly, human relations in general become reified, mediated by the exchange of commodities and money rather than by direct human connection.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] This leads to a breakdown in human communication and fosters a "tremendous loneliness".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In the "war of all against all" of civil society, each person views others not as fellows but as rivals and adversaries.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx's theory of alienation extends beyond a purely economic critique to encompass the totality of social existence under capitalism.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The economic foundation of alienation lies in the division of labour under the system of private property and exchange.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Political economists, Marx argued, mistook the historically specific, alienating division of labour for the universal "social character of labour".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Marx, the division of labour and private property are "identical expressions": the former describes the estranged activity, while the latter describes the estranged product.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The historical precondition for alienated labour is the separation of people from free access to the means of production and subsistence, which forces them into wage labour.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The system is governed by competition, which necessitates reification (*Verdinglichung*), the transformation of human beings and their relations into things.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Workers become commodities, bought and sold according to the laws of supply and demand.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] This reification permeates daily life, as when service workers come to see customers not as people but as the orders they represent.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Labour itself becomes abstract labour, a one-sided, machine-like activity, and the system fosters "inhuman, refined, unnatural and imaginary appetites" in the consumer that serve the accumulation of wealth rather than human fulfilment.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Alienation has profound political and moral dimensions.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Capitalist property relations negate human freedom.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Marx, this negation is rooted in the principle that a person's labour properly belongs to themselves; its expropriation by another is the basis of exploitation and the loss of freedom.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Politically, the modern state is an "illusory community", an "abstracted social power" that stands over and against atomised individuals.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] While formally guaranteeing "equal rights" for all citizens, the state serves to protect private property and thus sanctions a lack of freedom in real terms.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Human activity within this framework becomes "forced labour" under the yoke of another.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Morally, alienation overturns human values.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The system subordinates "being" to "having"; the "sense of having" replaces the full range of human senses.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Money becomes the "universal galvano-chemical power of Society", the ultimate mediator that "transforms fidelity into infidelity, love into hate, hate into love, virtue into vice".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The supersession of alienation, therefore, requires a radical political project: the "emancipation of the workers" which coincides with "universal human emancipation".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Marx, the overcoming of alienation is synonymous with the establishment of communism.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] He conceived of this new society not as a utopian ideal, but as the real movement that abolishes the present state of things.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The fundamental source of alienation, he argued, was "egoistic need" (both physical need and greed), which was itself a product of the nature of civil society and the institution of private property.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Consequently, the eradication of alienation could only be accomplished by changing the socioeconomic system.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] This would not be a regression to a primitive state of poverty, but the creation of a society that harnesses the productive forces developed by capitalism for the "full and free development of every individual".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The gradual disappearance of alienation requires the withering away of commodity production, economic scarcity, and the social division of labour (particularly between manual and intellectual labour).
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The abolition of private property and the division of labour would allow for the emergence of an "association of free men, working with the means of production held in common".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Novack, the goal of communism is the achievement of "free time for all", which becomes the measure of wealth and the "annihilator of alienation".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] A long-standing controversy surrounds the place of the theory of alienation in Marx's work, often framed as an opposition between a "young Marx" (the philosopher of alienation) and a "mature Marx" (the scientific political economist).
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Proponents of a "break" in Marx's development, such as the philosopher Louis Althusser, argue that he abandoned the humanistic and Hegelian-influenced concept of alienation in his later writings, replacing it with a more "scientific" analysis of economic structures.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] However, other scholars argue for a fundamental continuity in Marx's thought, asserting that the theory of alienation is not a youthful aberration but a central idea of his entire system.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Scholars such as Barry Padgett contend that the differentiation between a "young" and "mature" Marx, with the suggestion that the latter jettisons the concept, is a "false dichotomy".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Mandel argues that there was an "important evolution" in Marx's thought rather than a radical break or simple repetition.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Ollman suggests that the apparent change in terminology after 1844 is "overdone" and that even in his later economic works, Marx frequently resorted to the concepts and framework of his early writings when making connections across different disciplines.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The ironic remarks about "estrangement" in works like *The German Ideology* and *The Communist Manifesto* are not a rejection of the concept itself, but a critique of its abstract, idealist use by Marx's contemporaries, who divorced it from concrete social practice.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] According to these scholars, far from dropping the concept, Marx's later works concretise and elaborate the theory.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] While the specific term *Entfremdung* becomes less frequent in his published works like *Das Kapital*, the underlying conceptual structure remains.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] In works such as the *Grundrisse* (the rough draft for *Das Kapital*), the concept of alienation is massively present, linking the economic categories directly to the alienation of labour.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For example, in the *Grundrisse*, Marx writes that the "immense objective power set up by social labour... does not belong to the worker but to the personified conditions of production, i.e. to capital... this perversion and overturning is real, not imagined".
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] The publication of the notebooks in the mid-20th century was decisive in demonstrating this continuity.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Similarly, in *Das Kapital* itself, concepts like the fetishism of commodities and the domination of dead labour (capital) over living labour are direct elaborations of the theory of alienation.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] For Marx, fetishism is not a subjective problem but a "real power, a particular form of domination" that arises in a market economy.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] As Novack argues, the early concept of "alienated labor" was later developed into more precise economic categories, such as the distinction between concrete and abstract labour.
[src:social-metabolism/alienated-labor] Marx's life's work is thus seen as a single, coherent project: the analysis of the capitalist mode of production as a system of alienated labour and the articulation of the historical possibility of its transcendence.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Logically, it is an inference or an argument from one particular to another particular, as opposed to deduction, induction, and abduction.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It is also used where at least one of the premises, or the conclusion, is general rather than particular in nature.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It has the general form *A is to B as C is to D*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In a broader sense, analogical reasoning is a cognitive process of transferring meaning or information of a particular subject (the analog, or source) onto another (the target); and also the linguistic expression corresponding to such a process.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The term analogy can also refer to the relation between the source and the target themselves, which is often (though not always) a similarity, as in the biological notion of analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy plays a significant role in human thought processes.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It has been argued that analogy lies at "the core of cognition".
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The English word *analogy* derives from the Latin *analogia*, itself derived from the Greek *ἀναλογία*, "proportion", from *ana-* "upon, according to" [also "again", "anew"] + *logos* "ratio" [also "word, speech, reckoning"].
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy plays a significant role in problem solving, as well as decision making, argumentation, perception, generalization, memory, creativity, invention, prediction, emotion, explanation, conceptualization and communication.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It lies behind basic tasks such as the identification of places, objects and people, for example, in face perception and facial recognition systems.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Hofstadter has argued that analogy is "the core of cognition".
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] An analogy is not a figure of speech but a kind of thought.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Specific analogical language uses exemplification, comparisons, metaphors, similes, allegories, and parables, but *not* metonymy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Phrases like *and so on*, *and the like*, *as if*, and the very word *like* also rely on an analogical understanding by the receiver of a message including them.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy is important not only in ordinary language and common sense (where proverbs and idioms give many examples of its application) but also in science, philosophy, law and the humanities.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The concepts of association, comparison, correspondence, mathematical and morphological homology, homomorphism, iconicity, isomorphism, metaphor, resemblance, and similarity are closely related to analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In cognitive linguistics, the notion of conceptual metaphor may be equivalent to that of analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy is also a basis for any comparative arguments as well as experiments whose results are transmitted to objects that have been not under examination (e.g., experiments on rats when results are applied to humans).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy has been studied and discussed since classical antiquity by philosophers, scientists, theologists and lawyers.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The last few decades have shown a renewed interest in analogy, most notably in cognitive science.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In ancient Greek the word *αναλογια* (*analogia*) originally meant proportionality, in the mathematical sense, and it was indeed sometimes translated to Latin as *proportio*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy was understood as identity of relation between any two ordered pairs, whether of mathematical nature or not.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy and abstraction are different cognitive processes, and analogy is often an easier one.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This analogy is not comparing *all* the properties between a hand and a foot, but rather comparing the *relationship* between a hand and its palm to a foot and its sole.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] While a hand and a foot have many dissimilarities, the analogy focuses on their similarity in having an inner surface.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This relation is not apparent in some lexical definitions of *palm* and *sole*, where the former is defined as *the inner surface of the hand*, and the latter as *the underside of the foot*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Kant's *Critique of Judgment* held to this notion of analogy, arguing that there can be exactly the same relation between two completely different objects.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Greek philosophers such as Plato and Aristotle used a wider notion of analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] They saw analogy as a shared abstraction.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogous objects did not share necessarily a relation, but also an idea, a pattern, a regularity, an attribute, an effect or a philosophy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] These authors also accepted that comparisons, metaphors and "images" (allegories) could be used as arguments, and sometimes they called them *analogies*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogies should also make those abstractions easier to understand and give confidence to those who use them.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Ibn Taymiyya, Francis Bacon and later John Stuart Mill argued that analogy is simply a special case of induction.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Contemporary cognitive scientists use a wide notion of analogy, extensionally close to that of Plato and Aristotle, but framed by Gentner's (1983) structure-mapping theory.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The same idea of mapping between source and target is used by conceptual metaphor and conceptual blending theorists.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Structure mapping theory concerns both psychology and computer science.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] According to this view, analogy depends on the mapping or alignment of the elements of source and target.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The mapping takes place not only between objects, but also between relations of objects and between relations of relations.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The whole mapping yields the assignment of a predicate or a relation to the target.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Structure mapping theory has been applied and has found considerable confirmation in psychology.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It has had reasonable success in computer science and artificial intelligence (see below).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Some studies extended the approach to specific subjects, such as metaphor and similarity.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Logicians analyze how analogical reasoning is used in arguments from analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In the field of testing, the colon notation of ratios and equality is often borrowed, so that the example above might be rendered, "Smile : mouth :: wink : eye" and pronounced the same way.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In historical linguistics and word formation, analogy is the process that alters words-forms perceived as breaking rules or ignoring general patterns to more typical forms that follow them.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] For example, the English verb *help* once had the simple past-tense form *holp* and the past participle form *holpen*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] These older forms have now been discarded and replaced by *helped*, which came about through the analogy that many other past-tense forms use the *-ed* ending (*jumped*, *carried*, *defeated*, etc.).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogies do not always lead to words shifting to fit rules; sometimes, they can also leading to the breaking of rules; one example is the American English past tense form of *dive*: *dove*, formed on analogy with words such as *drive* to *drove* or *strive* to *strove*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy is also a term used in the Neogrammarian school of thought as a catch-all to describe any morphological change in a language that cannot be explained merely sound change or borrowing.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogies are mainly used as a means of creating new ideas and hypotheses, or testing them, which is called a heuristic function of analogical reasoning.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogical arguments can also be probative, meaning that they serve as a means of proving the rightness of particular theses and theories.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This application of analogical reasoning in science is debatable.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogy can be used in theoretical and applied sciences in the form of models or simulations which can be considered as strong indications of probable correctness.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Other, much weaker, analogies may also assist in understanding and describing nuanced or key functional behaviours of systems that are otherwise difficult to grasp or prove.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] For instance, an analogy used in physics textbooks compares electrical circuits to hydraulic circuits.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Another example is the analogue ear based on electrical, electronic or mechanical devices.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Some types of analogies can have a precise mathematical formulation through the concept of isomorphism.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In detail, this means that if two mathematical structures are of the same type, an analogy between them can be thought of as a bijection which preserves some or all of the relevant structure.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] For example, $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ and $\mathbb {C}$ are isomorphic as vector spaces, but the complex numbers, $\mathbb {C}$ , have more structure than $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ does: $\mathbb {C}$ is a field as well as a vector space.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Category theory takes the idea of mathematical analogy much further with the concept of functors.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Given two categories C and D, a functor *f* from C to D can be thought of as an analogy between C and D, because *f* has to map objects of C to objects of D and arrows of C to arrows of D in such a way that the structure of their respective parts is preserved.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This is similar to the structure mapping theory of analogy of Dedre Gentner, because it formalises the idea of analogy as a function which makes certain conditions true.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The issue of how Large Language Models relate to human analogical thinking is a matter of current research (as of 2025).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] By 2006, a computer algorithm using the Vector Space Model (VSM) had achieved human-level performance on multiple-choice analogy questions from the SAT test.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The algorithm measures the similarity of relations between pairs of words (e.g., the similarity between the pairs HAND:PALM and FOOT:SOLE) by statistically analysing a large collection of text.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It answers SAT questions by selecting the choice with the highest relational similarity.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The analogical reasoning in the human mind is free of the false inferences plaguing conventional artificial intelligence models, (called *systematicity*).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Wilson use category theory to mathematically demonstrate how such reasoning could arise naturally by using relationships between the internal arrows that keep the internal structures of the categories rather than the mere relationships between the objects (called "representational states").
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Thus, the mind, and more intelligent AIs, may use analogies between domains whose internal structures transform naturally and reject those that do not.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Keith Holyoak and Paul Thagard (1997) developed their multiconstraint theory within structure mapping theory.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] They defend that the "coherence" of an analogy depends on structural consistency, semantic similarity and purpose.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Structural consistency is the highest when the analogy is an isomorphism, although lower levels can be used as well.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Similarity demands that the mapping connects similar elements and relationships between source and target, at any level of abstraction.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It is the highest when there are identical relations and when connected elements have many identical attributes.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] An analogy achieves its purpose if it helps solve the problem at hand.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The multiconstraint theory faces some difficulties when there are multiple sources, but these can be overcome.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Hummel and Holyoak (2005) recast the multiconstraint theory within a neural network architecture.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] A problem for the multiconstraint theory arises from its concept of similarity, which, in this respect, is not obviously different from analogy itself.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Computer applications demand that there are some *identical* attributes or relations at some level of abstraction.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The model was extended (Doumas, Hummel, and Sandhofer, 2008) to learn relations from unstructured examples (providing the only current account of how symbolic representations can be learned from examples).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Mark Keane and Brayshaw (1988) developed their *Incremental Analogy Machine* (IAM) to include working memory constraints as well as structural, semantic and pragmatic constraints, so that a subset of the base analogue is selected and mapping from base to target occurs in series.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Empirical evidence shows that humans are better at using and creating analogies when the information is presented in an order where an item and its analogue are placed together.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Eqaan Doug and his team challenged the shared structure theory and mostly its applications in computer science.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] They argue that there is no clear line between perception, including high-level perception, and analogical thinking.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In fact, analogy occurs not only after, but also before and at the same time as high-level perception.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In high-level perception, humans make representations by selecting relevant information from low-level stimuli.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Perception is necessary for analogy, but analogy is also necessary for high-level perception.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Chalmers et al. concludes that analogy actually is high-level perception.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] (1998) claim that this is only a metaphor.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It has been argued (Morrison and Dietrich 1995) that Hofstadter's and Gentner's groups do not defend opposite views, but are instead dealing with different aspects of analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Based on Hofstadter's ideas, abstract analogy-making tasks (using both perceptual and symbolic inputs) may be learned by a connectionist network using a two-step, feed-forward network.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In anatomy, two anatomical structures are considered to be *analogous* when they serve similar functions but are not evolutionarily related, such as the legs of vertebrates and the legs of insects.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogous structures are the result of independent evolution and should be contrasted with structures which shared an evolutionary line.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Often a physical prototype is built to model and represent some other physical object.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] For example, wind tunnels are used to test scale models of wings and aircraft which are analogous to (correspond to) full-size wings and aircraft.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] For example, the MONIAC (an analogue computer) used the flow of water in its pipes as an analogue to the flow of money in an economy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Where two or more biological or physical participants meet, they communicate and the stresses produced describe internal models of the participants.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Pask in his conversation theory asserts an analogy that describes both similarities and differences between any pair of the participants' internal models or concepts exists.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In historical science, comparative historical analysis often uses the concept of analogy and analogical reasoning.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Recent methods involving calculation operate on large document archives, allowing for analogical or corresponding terms from the past to be found as a response to random questions by users (e.g., Myanmar - Burma) and explained.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogical reasoning plays a very important part in morality.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This may be because morality is supposed to be impartial and fair.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] If it is wrong to do something in a situation A, and situation B corresponds to A in all related features, then it is also wrong to perform that action in situation B.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Moral particularism accepts such reasoning, instead of deduction and induction, since only the first can be used regardless of any moral principles.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Structure mapping, originally proposed by Dedre Gentner, is a theory in psychology that describes the psychological processes involved in reasoning through, and learning from, analogies.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] More specifically, this theory aims to describe how familiar knowledge, or knowledge about a base domain, can be used to inform an individual's understanding of a less familiar idea, or a target domain.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] According to this theory, individuals view their knowledge of ideas, or domains, as interconnected structures.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In other words, a domain is viewed as consisting of objects, their properties, and the relationships that characterise their interactions.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Finding deeper similarities by mapping other relationships of a base domain to the target domain.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Cross-checking those findings against existing knowledge of the target domain.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In general, it has been found that people prefer analogies where the two systems correspond highly to each other (e.g. have similar relationships across the domains as opposed to just having similar objects across domains) when these people try to compare and contrast the systems.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This is also known as the systematicity principle.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] An example that has been used to illustrate structure mapping theory comes from Gentner and Gentner (1983) and uses the base domain of flowing water and the target domain of electricity.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In a system of flowing water, the water is carried through pipes and the rate of water flow is determined by the pressure of the water towers or hills.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This relationship corresponds to that of electricity flowing through a circuit.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In a circuit, the electricity is carried through wires and the current, or rate of flow of electricity, is determined by the voltage, or electrical pressure.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Given the similarity in structure, or structural alignment, between these domains, structure mapping theory would predict that relationships from one of these domains, would be inferred in the other using analogy.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Children do not always need prompting to make comparisons in order to learn abstract relationships.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Eventually, children undergo a relational shift, after which they begin seeing similar relations across different situations instead of merely looking at matching objects.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This is critical in their cognitive development as continuing to focus on specific objects would reduce children's ability to learn abstract patterns and reason analogically.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Interestingly, some researchers have proposed that children's basic brain functions (i.e., working memory and inhibitory control) do not drive this relational shift.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Instead, it is driven by their relational knowledge, such as having labels for the objects that make the relationships clearer(see previous section).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] However, there is not enough evidence to determine whether the relational shift is actually because basic brain functions become better or relational knowledge becomes deeper.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Additionally, research has identified several factors that may increase the likelihood that a child may spontaneously engage in comparison and learn an abstract relationship, without the need for prompts.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Comparison is more likely when the objects to be compared are close together in space and/or time, are highly similar (although not so similar that they match, which interfere with identifying relationships), or share common labels.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In law, analogy is a method of resolving issues on which there is no previous authority.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The legal use of analogy is distinguished by the need to use a legally relevant basis for drawing an analogy between two situations.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It may be applied to various forms of legal authority, including statutory law and case law.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In the civil law tradition, analogy is most typically used for filling gaps in a statutory scheme.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In the common law tradition, it is most typically used for extending the scope of precedent.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The use of analogy in both traditions is broadly described by the traditional maxim *Ubi eadem est ratio, ibi idem ius* (where the reason is the same, the law is the same).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Analogies as defined in rhetoric are a comparison between words, but an analogy more generally can also be used to illustrate and teach.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] To enlighten pupils on the relations between or within certain concepts, items or phenomena, a teacher may refer to other concepts, items or phenomena that pupils are more familiar with.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It may help to create or clarify one theory (or theoretical model) via the workings of another theory (or theoretical model).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Thus an analogy, as used in teaching, would be comparing a topic that students are already familiar with, with a new topic that is being introduced, so that students can get a better understanding of the new topic by relating back to existing knowledge.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] This can be particularly helpful when the analogy serves across different disciplines: indeed, there are various teaching innovations now emerging that use sight-based analogies for teaching and research across subjects such as science and the humanities.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The theological exploration of this subject is called the *analogia entis*.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The consequence of this theory is that all true statements concerning God (excluding the concrete details of Jesus' earthly life) are rough analogies, without implying any falsehood.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The use of theological statements in syllogisms must take into account their analogical essence, in that every analogy breaks down when stretched beyond its intended meaning.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In traditional Christian doctrine, the Trinity is a Mystery of Faith that has been revealed, not something obvious or derivable from first principles or found in any thing in the created world.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Because of this, the use of analogies to understand the Trinity is common and perhaps necessary.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The Trinity is a combination of the words "tri," meaning "three," and "unity," meaning "one." The "Threeness" refers to the persons of the Trinity, while the "Oneness" refers to substance or being.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Many analogies have been used to explain the Trinity, however, all analogies fail when taken too far.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Examples of these are the analogies that state that the Trinity is like water and its different states (solid, liquid, gas) or like an egg with its different parts (shell, yolk, and egg white).
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] However, these analogies, if taken too far, could teach the heresies of modalism (water states) and partialism (parts of egg), which are contrary to the Christian understanding of the Trinity.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The analogy of notes of a chord, say C major, is a sufficient analogy for the Trinity.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The notes C, E, and G individually fill the whole of the "heard" space, but when all notes come together, we have a homogenized sound within the same space with distinctive, equal notes.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] One more analogy used is one that uses the mythological dog, Cerberus, that guards the gates of Hades.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] While the dog itself is a single organism—speaking to its substance—Cerberus has different centers of awareness due to its three heads, each of which has the same dog nature.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] In some Protestant theology, "analogy" may itself be used analogously in terms, more in a sense of "rule" or "exemplar": for example the concept "analogia fidei" has been proposed as an alternative to the concept *analogia entis* but named analogously.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] Islamic jurisprudence makes ample use of analogy as a means of making conclusions from outside sources of law.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] The bounds and rules employed to make analogical deduction vary greatly between madhhabs and to a lesser extent individual scholars.
[src:social-metabolism/analogical-reasoning] It is nonetheless a generally accepted source of law within jurisprudential epistemology, with the chief opposition to it forming the dhahiri (ostensiblist) school.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] In layman's terms, anthropogenic metabolism indicates the human impact on the world by the modern industrialized world.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Much of these impacts include waste management, ecological footprints, water footprints, and flow analysis (i.e., the rate at which each human depleted the energy around them).
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most anthropogenic metabolism happens in developed countries.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] A water footprint is the amount of water that each person uses in their daily lives.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most of the world's water is salt water which cannot be used in human food or water supplies.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Therefore, the freshwater sources that were once plentiful are now being diminished due to anthropogenic metabolism of the growing population.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The water footprint encompasses how much fresh water is needed for each consumer's needs.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Allan, "there is a huge impact of water use on stores of surface and groundwater and on flows to which water is returned after use.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] These impacts are shown to be particularly high for manufacturing industries.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] For example, that there are less than 10 economies worldwide that have a significant water surplus, but that these economies have successfully met, or have the potential to meet, the water deficits of the other 190 economies.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Consumers enjoy the delusion of food and water security provided by virtual water trade.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] In addition, the ecological footprint is a more economical and land-focused way of looking at human impact.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Developed countries tend to have higher ecological footprints, which do not strictly correspond to a country's total population.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] According to research by Dias de Oliveira, Vaughan and Rykiel, "The Ecological Footprint...is an accounting tool based on two fundamental concepts, sustainability and carrying capacity.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] One of the major cycles that humans can contribute to that cause a major impact on climate change is the nitrogen cycle.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] This comes from nitrogen fertilizers that humans use.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Gruber and Galloway have researched, "The massive acceleration of the nitrogen cycle caused by the production and industrial use of artificial nitrogen fertilizers worldwide has led to a range of environmental problems.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The carbon cycle is another major contributor to climate change primarily from anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] A couple examples of how humans contribute to the carbon in the atmosphere is by burning fossil fuels and deforestation.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Impact of climate change extend beyond humans.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] There is a forecast for extinctions of species because of their habitats being affected.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] There are major impacts on the marine systems as a result of anthropogenic metabolism, according to Blaustein, the dramatic findings indicate that "every square kilometer [is] affected by some anthropogenic driver of ecological change".
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The negative effects of anthropogenic metabolism are seen through the water footprint, ecological footprint, carbon cycle, and the nitrogen cycle.
[src:social-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Studies on the marine ecosystem that show major impacts by humans and developed countries which include more industries, thus more anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Social metabolic processes begin with the human *appropriation* of materials and energy from nature.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] These can be *transformed* and *circulated* to be *consumed* and *excreted* finally back to nature itself.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Each of these processes has a different environmental impact depending on how it is performed, the amount of materials and energy involved in the process, the area where it occurs, the time available or nature's regenerative capacity.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Social metabolism represents an extension of the metabolism concept from biological organisms like human bodies to the biophysical basis of society.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] In capitalist societies, humans build and operate mines and farms, oil refineries and power stations, factories and infrastructure to supply the energy and material flows needed for the physical reproduction of a specific culture.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] In-use stocks, which comprise buildings, vehicles, appliances, infrastructure, etc., are built up and maintained by the different industrial processes that are part of social metabolism.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] These stocks then provide services to people in the form of shelter, transportation, or communication.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] John Bellamy Foster has thus developed the concept of metabolic rift to develop Marx's understanding of the deleterious effect of capitalism on ecosystems.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Society and its metabolism together form an autopoietic system, a complex system that reproduces itself.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Neither culture nor social metabolism can reproduce themselves in isolation.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Humans need food and shelter, which is delivered by social metabolism, and the latter needs humans to operate it.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Social or socioeconomic metabolism stipulates that human society and its interaction with nature form a complex self-reproducing system, and it can therefore be seen as paradigm for studying the biophysical basis of human societies under the aspect of self-reproduction.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] "A common paradigm can facilitate model combination and integration, which can lead to more robust and comprehensive interdisciplinary assessments of sustainable development strategies. ...
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] The concept of social metabolism emerged in the nineteenth century, which was a time of scientific integration and reciprocity among naturalists and social scholars.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] The evolutionary perspective, particularly analogical reasoning, provided crossties between natural and social sciences.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] It was only in the late 1970s that the human exceptionalism paradigm was rigorously questioned, leading to the birth of environmental sociology.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] The concept of social metabolism has been used in historical research as a framework to describe the development of human societies over time.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Particularly important in this field is the work done by the German historian Rolf Sieferle on the socio-ecological patterns of societies.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Sieferle identified three main regimes that characterised human history: hunting-gathering, agrarian and industrial.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] The hunting-gathering regime relied on "passive solar energy utilization", as in this configuration humans relied mainly on products of recent photosynthesis, namely plants and animals for food and firewood for heat.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] This resulted in highly nomadic societies and low population density.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Eventually, the Neolithic Revolution allowed societies to switch to an agrarian regime based on "active solar energy utilization".
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Humans started to modify their environment more systematically through deforestation in order maximise the exploitation of land and sun for farming to produce food for humans and for livestock.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] This led to sedentary societies, increased human labour burden and to higher population growth, which boosted the development of more structured social hierarchies and dynamics.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] The invention of the steam engine in the 16th century triggered the emergence of the industrial regime, that relies on fossil fuels as its main energy source.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] This led to the industrial socio-ecological pattern that regulates human society as we now it today.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Following Sieferle's footsteps, other social scientists eventually tried to reconstruct human history through social metabolism, also through quantitative analyses and indicators.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Among them it is worth mentioning the Total Primary Energy Supply (TPES), the Domestic Energy Consumption (DEC), the Human Appropriation of Net Primary Production (HANPP) and others.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Using energetic metabolism as a proxy for human development has important implications not only for historical analysis, but also for the elaboration of future scenarios.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] According to many studies, peak fossil fuel (i.e. the maximum rate of fossil fuels extraction on a global scale) has already been reached or is likely to be reached soon.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Understanding what will be the next main energy source and conversion technology of human societies in the future has important policy and societal implications.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Studies of social metabolism can be carried out at different levels of system aggregation, see material flow analysis.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] In material flow accounting, for example, the inputs and outputs of materials and energy of a particular state or region, as well as imports and exports, are analysed.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] Such studies are facilitated by the ease of access to information about commercial transactions.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] There are different schools of thought concerning social metabolism, each with its own accounting method.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] The scholar who laid the foundations for MEFA is Marina Fischer-Kowalski, while MuSIASEM developed around Mario Giampietro and Kozo Mayumi.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] While MEFA, primarily focusses its research on national economies across time and space, MuSIASEM primarily focusses its research on contemporary economies, herein they focus on specific subsectors of the economy.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] This brings with it some methodological differences as well, in the MEFA school of thought, researchers have been more geared toward standardizing data collection as much as possible, which would result in an easier comparison between a wide range of cases and data.
[src:social-metabolism/social-metabolism] On the other hand, in the MuSIASEM school, scholars have been more reluctant to do this, they prefer to have a tailor-made form of accounting for every case, operating within a predetermined 'grammar'.
